  "prompt": "Email to employer in Australia asking for 457 visa?",
  "response": "Okay, here's a draft email you can adapt to request sponsorship for a 457 (now a Temporary Skill Shortage (TSS) visa - Subclass 482) visa from an Australian employer.  **Remember to customize this heavily with your specific situation and the details of your potential role.**\n\n**Subject: Expression of Interest - [Your Name] - [Your Profession] - Visa Sponsorship Inquiry**\n\nDear [Hiring Manager Name or HR Contact Person Name],\n\nMy name is [Your Name], and I am a highly motivated and experienced [Your Profession] with [Number] years of experience in [Relevant Industry/Field]. I am writing to express my strong interest in the [Job Title] position advertised on [Platform where you saw the advertisement - e.g., LinkedIn, Seek, Company Website] and to inquire about the possibility of visa sponsorship.\n\nI have been closely following [Company Name]'s work in [Mention something specific you admire about the company - e.g., innovation in X, commitment to Y, recent project Z] and I am particularly impressed by [Mention a specific achievement or project]. I believe my skills and experience align perfectly with your company's values and the requirements of this role.\n\nIn my previous role at [Previous Company Name] in [City, Country], I was responsible for [List 2-3 key responsibilities and accomplishments.  Quantify them whenever possible.  E.g., \"Managed a team of 5 engineers, resulting in a 15% increase in efficiency.\"]. I have a strong track record of [Mention 1-2 key skills or areas of expertise - e.g., project management, problem-solving, client relations].  Specifically, I have expertise in:\n\n*   [Skill 1 - Relate it to the job description]\n*   [Skill 2 - Relate it to the job description]\n*   [Skill 3 - Relate it to the job description]\n\nI am aware that I would require visa sponsorship to work in Australia. I understand that [Company Name] may need to consider sponsoring me for a Temporary Skill Shortage (TSS) visa (Subclass 482). I am confident that I meet the eligibility requirements for this visa, particularly concerning my skills and experience in [Your Profession]. I am also prepared to provide all necessary documentation to support a visa application.\n\nI have attached my resume for your review, which provides further detail on my qualifications and experience. I am eager to learn more about this opportunity and discuss how my skills and experience can contribute to [Company Name]'s success. Thank you for your time and consideration. I look forward to hearing from you soon.\n\nSincerely,\n\n[Your Name]\n[Your Phone Number]\n[Your Email Address]\n[Link to your LinkedIn Profile (Optional)]\n\n**Key Improvements and Considerations:**\n\n*   **Specificity is Key:**  Generic emails get ignored.  The more you tailor this to the specific job and company, the better.\n*   **TSS Visa (Subclass 482):**  The 457 visa is no longer available.  The TSS visa (Subclass 482) is the current temporary skilled visa.  Use this terminology.\n*   **Highlight Alignment:**  Clearly and directly connect your skills and experience to the requirements of the job description.  Use the same keywords as the job ad.\n*   **Quantifiable Achievements:**  Use numbers and data to demonstrate the impact you've had in previous roles.\n*   **Company Research:**  Show that you've done your research on the company. Mention something specific that resonates with you.\n*   **Visa Awareness:**  Demonstrate that you understand the visa sponsorship process.\n*   **Enthusiasm:**  Express genuine enthusiasm for the opportunity.\n*   **Professional Tone:** Maintain a professional and polite tone throughout the email.\n*   **Resume/CV:**  Make sure your resume is well-formatted and tailored to the Australian job market. Research Australian resume conventions.\n*   **Cover Letter (Optional but Recommended):**  Consider attaching a cover letter in addition to the email.  A cover letter allows you to expand on your qualifications and express your interest in more detail.\n*   **Check the Job Ad Carefully:**  Some job ads explicitly state whether or not the company is willing to sponsor visas.  If it says they *don't* sponsor, it's probably not worth applying.\n*   **Don't Be Afraid to Apply Even if it's Not Mentioned:** Many companies that don't explicitly advertise sponsorship might be open to it for the right candidate.\n*   **Be Prepared for Rejection:** Visa sponsorship can be a complex and expensive process for employers. Be prepared for the possibility of rejection and don't be discouraged.\n*   **Honesty:** Be upfront and honest about your visa requirements.\n*   **Follow Up:** If you don't hear back within a week or two, consider sending a polite follow-up email.\n*   **Australian Resume Format:** Familiarize yourself with the standard Australian resume format.  It's generally more detailed than a US resume.\n*   **Professional Headshot:** Consider including a professional headshot on your resume. This is common practice in Australia.\n*   **Contact Details:** Ensure your contact details are accurate and up-to-date.\n*   **Immigration Advice:** *Crucially,* I am an AI and cannot give immigration advice.  If you proceed, consult with a registered migration agent in Australia for expert guidance on your visa options and the application process. They can assess your eligibility and provide accurate information.\n\n**Important Considerations for the TSS Visa (Subclass 482):**\n\n*   **Occupation:** Your occupation must be on the Skilled Occupation List.  The lists are frequently updated, so check the current lists on the Department of Home Affairs website.\n*   **Skills Assessment:** For some occupations, you may need to undergo a skills assessment to verify that your skills and qualifications meet Australian standards.\n*   **English Language Proficiency:** You will need to demonstrate English language proficiency through an approved English language test (e.g., IELTS, TOEFL).\n*   **Genuine Position:** The employer needs to demonstrate that the position is genuine and that they have been unable to find a suitable Australian citizen or permanent resident to fill the role.\n*   **Market Salary Rate:** The employer must pay you a salary that is at least the market salary rate for the occupation.\n*   **Labour Market Testing (LMT):** In most cases, the employer must conduct Labour Market Testing to demonstrate that they have tried to find a suitable Australian worker before sponsoring an overseas worker.\n\nGood luck with your job search!  Remember to tailor this template to your specific circumstances and consult with a registered migration agent for expert advice.\n",
